{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3355042,"name":"","username":"Jelatinone","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/f475e1/{size}.png","created_at":"2024-04-08T14:51:24.956Z","cooked":"

With the end of my team’s competition season I’ve transitioned into brainstorming ideas for off-season (per this post), one of which being an Machine-Learning based project that would provide Object and Robot Detection, but moreover with the end goal of providing other relevant information about detected robots, like their relative position (robot-pose), and combining existing data from when the robot was last detected on the field (so we also need to detect team number for tracking specific robots).

I’ve seen other relevant models such as Dataset Collab, which to my understanding does provide sufficient robot detection and object detection for this year’s game, but does not provide features like estimating the relative pose of a detected bot based on this model.

My end goal in this project would be to create a plugin, which can easily be integrated into existing code and allow for a Pathfinder (such as Path Planner’s AD* Algorithm) to be given the robot-pose from this model and avoid them. Additionally at a more advanced scale to estimate what robots have ownership of what game pieces, that way during autonomous our robot could alter its path around robots and to unclaimed game pieces. And possibly further down the line, combining this with match recordings for scouting if the model can make accurate-enough predictions.

However my main issue, rather than being a lack of experience, is really the size and labeling of data, and training-downtime on the model. The aforementioned Dataset Collab contains somewhere along 30,000 Labelled Images in it’s dataset, and still isn’t entirely accurate. I’ve also looked into Synthetic Data approaches, where I could perhaps use Blender to create my own rendered scenes and feed it to a model, providing control over both the labeling (already know where and what the game pieces look like) and size of dataset (can easily create more data). But how feasible is it for within the bounds of now, until the end of the next competition-season’s build season create a fully developed model (much less even an API that allows for configuration with different cameras & setups from what i’ll be using) that can meet my requirements, and how can I go about doing it?

TL;DR: How can I make an AI model (and gather enough data) to sufficiently estimate the dimensions, position, and Team Number of another robot?

The first step is to start small. Before you begin trying to do something complicated like avoiding other robots, first make sure you can do the basics such as detecting them. Then start working your way up, figuring where they are and where they are headed.

Break your problem into smaller ones and don’t try to do everything at once. I would choose one (estimating robot poses, guessing robot size, or detecting team number) and begin working on that. This may be a big project and you will likely be overwhelmed if you try to do it all at once. Get something started and you will see that things will begin moving.
